Join the two dataframes together and sample zip codes:

Code 
zip_codes_weighted <- zip_codes_clean %>%
  mutate(
    sampling_weight = if_else(distance_from_gb <= 30, 
                               # for distances under 30 miles, use an inverse power law
                               1 / (distance_from_gb + 1), # inverse power law
                               # for distances over 30 miles, use an extremely low weight
                               0.001
    ))

set.seed(713)
zip_codes_sample <- bind_rows(zip_codes_sample_sb, zip_codes_sample_ventura) %>% # joining ventura and sb samples
  mutate(zip_code = sample(zip_codes_weighted$zip_code, 200, replace = TRUE, prob = zip_codes_weighted$sampling_weight)) %>%  #sample zip codes based on which ones are closer, using the function we made
  left_join(zip_codes_clean, by = "zip_code") # join with zip_codes_clean

Calculate travel cost

Code 
# calculate travel cost
travel_cost <- zip_codes_sample %>% # so each zip code has its respective city and county
  mutate(travel_cost = case_when(
    travel_method == "personal_vehicle" ~ (4.5/21 * distance_from_gb) + (median_income*(1/525600) * time_to_gb), # cost of gas (average price of gas in SB is $4.50/gallon) * (average US mid-size miles per gallon) * distance to gb plus the time it takes to get to gb # income $/ year * (year / minutes in a year) * time to gb (minutes/trip)
    travel_method == "carpool" ~ (2.25/21 * distance_from_gb) + (median_income*(1/525600) * time_to_gb), # half the cost of gas (assumption!!) * distance to gb plus the time it takes to get to gb
    travel_method == "public_transportation" ~ 6 + (median_income*(1/525600) * time_to_gb), # flat fee to get to gb (SB day pass, would also apply to those coming from Ventura) using the bus plus the time it takes to get to gb
    travel_method == "bicycle" ~ median_income*(1/525600) * time_to_gb * 3, # time it takes to get to gb... distance in miles to gb * (60min/10 miles) using the average speed of a bike is 10 miles per hour
    # https://cyced.cc/blog/how-long-does-it-take-to-cycle-10-miles-with-examples/#:~:text=How%20long%20to%20cycle%2010,10%20miles%20will%20be%20reduced.
    travel_method == "walking" ~ median_income*(1/525600) * time_to_gb * 9 # also only time it takes to get to gb... distance in miles to gb * (60min/3 miles) using the average speed of a walker is 3 miles per hour
    # https://www.healthline.com/health/exercise-fitness/average-walking-speed#average-speed-by-age
  ))

Demand curve and consumer surplus

Now, based on the travel cost and the number of respondents based on zip code sample frequency, we can determine the demand curve and consumer surplus.

Code 
# determine zip code representation
visitor_frequency <- travel_cost %>%
  group_by(zip_code) %>%
  summarize(
    visitor_count = n() # number of respondents from this zip code
  ) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(
    visitor_frequency = visitor_count / nrow(travel_cost) # frequency of respondents from this zip code
  )

travel_cost_w_frequency <- travel_cost %>%
  left_join(visitor_frequency, by = "zip_code") %>% 
  mutate(travel_cost_visit = travel_cost * visitor_frequency) # $/trip * # of trips = $!

# distribution of visitors by zip code
ggplot(travel_cost_w_frequency, aes(x = visitor_count)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, fill = "darkblue", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Respondents by Zip Code",
       x = "Number of Respondents",
       y = "Frequency of Zip Codes") +
  theme_minimal()

Code 
# plotting visitor frequency by mean travel cost (which is the demand curve, we will see this later too)
ggplot(travel_cost_w_frequency, aes(x = visitor_count, y = travel_cost)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "cornflowerblue", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Visitor Frequency by Travel Cost per Trip",
       x = "Total number of visits in January and February",
       y = "Price of a visit ($)") +
  theme_minimal()

travel_cost_model <- lm(travel_cost ~ visitor_count, data = travel_cost_w_frequency)

\[Travel\ Cost = Î²0 + Î²1 * Visits\] \[Travel\ Cost = 17.30 - 0.6754 * Visits\]

To find WTP, we want to plot the demand curve, which is typically the inverse of our regression model:

Code

  geom_point(alpha = 0.7) +

       y = "Price of a visit ($)") +

Code 
# now, plot $$Travel \ Cost = 13.52771 - 0.43740 * Visits$$
travel_cost_demand_curve_plot +
  geom_abline(intercept = 17.30, slope = -0.6754, color = "cornflowerblue", lwd = 1)

Calculate the consumer surplus by integrating this curve:

Code 
demand_goleta_beach <- function(x){
  17.30 - 0.6754 * x
}

x_int <- 17.30/0.6754

consumer_surplus <- integrate(demand_goleta_beach, 0, x_int)
consumer_surplus
221.565 with absolute error < 2.5e-12
Code 
# $221.565 with absolute error < 2.5e-12 average willingness to pay for two months of goleta beach usage

# create a data frame for the demand curve
demand_curve_data <- data.frame(
  x = seq(0, x_int, length.out = 100),
  y = demand_goleta_beach(seq(0, x_int, length.out = 100))
)

ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = travel_cost_w_frequency, aes(x = visitor_count, y = travel_cost), alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_line(data = demand_curve_data, aes(x = x, y = y), color = "cornflowerblue", lwd = 1) +
  geom_ribbon(data = demand_curve_data, aes(x = x, ymin = 0, ymax = y),
              fill = "cornflowerblue", alpha = 0.5) +
    labs(title = "Average WTP of Goleta Beach Visitors",
       x = "Number of visits in January and February",
       y = "Price of a visit ($)") +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, x_int), ylim = c(0, max(travel_cost_w_frequency$travel_cost)))

Now, assuming that is a value determined over two months, we can divide the WTP by the number of days surveyed to get a daily value:

\[Consumer\ Surplus = \int_{0}^{25.62} 17.30 - 0.6754 * Visits\]

Code 
consumer_surplus_daily <- consumer_surplus$value / (31 + 28)
consumer_surplus_daily # $3.755339/day
[1] 3.755339

Water Quality Evaluation for Goleta Beach

Data found from https://www.waterboards.ca.gov/water_issues/programs/beaches/beach_water_quality/, specifically https://www.waterboards.ca.gov/water_issues/programs/beaches/search_beach_mon.html. The data is from the California State Water Resources Control Board. The data is from the Santa Barbara County Beaches. The data is from 2000 to 2024, though data was downloaded from 2010 to 2024.

  labs(title = "Goleta Beach Water Quality (2023)",
       x = "Date",
       y = "Result (MPN/100mL)") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 104, linetype = "dashed", color = "black", size = 0.5) + # criteria for enterococcus.  State Health Standard: Based on a single sample, the density of bacteria in water from each sampling station at a public beach or public water contact sports area shall not exceed: 104 
  theme_minimal()

Code 
# determine how many days on average in january and february have enterococcus levels above 104 MPN/100mL
days_exceeded_ent <- goleta_beach_qual_mdy %>% 
  filter(parameter %in% "Enterococcus") %>% 
  filter(month(sample_date) %in% 1:2) %>% # filter for jan and feb
  mutate(above_threshold = ifelse(result > 104, 1, 0)) %>% # state health criteria
  group_by(year(sample_date), month(sample_date)) %>% # group by year and month
  summarize(proportion_of_month_exceeded = as.numeric(sum(above_threshold)/n())) %>%  # proportion of days in the month that exceeded the threshold
  mutate(percent_of_month_exceeded = proportion_of_month_exceeded * 100) # convert to percentage

# make a table of the results

Value lost if 28% of days in January and February are above the threshold

Code 
# calculate the value lost if 28% of days in January and February are above the threshold

days_lost_jan_feb <- 0.28 * 59 # average of 17 days the beach is unsuitable for swimming in january and february
days_lost_jan_feb # 16.52 days lost
[1] 16.52
Code 
value_lost <- days_lost_jan_feb * consumer_surplus_daily # 28% of days in january and february times the value of the visit for each of those days is the value of the days lost
value_lost # $62.0382 lost in value per person
[1] 62.0382

Based on BEACON, there are 500,000 person-days per year at Goleta Beach, which means there are 500,000 visits every year. Therefore, we our value of daily consumer surplus is the value of one person-day.

Code 
# based on 500,000 person-days a year visit GB from BEACON:
value_per_year <- consumer_surplus_daily*500000
value_per_year # $1,877,669 per year
[1] 1877669
Code 
# value for two months of the year (jan and feb):
jan_feb_value_visitor_frequency <- value_per_year * (2/12) # two months of 12 months
jan_feb_value_visitor_frequency # $312,944.9
[1] 312944.9
Code 
# value lost if 28% of days in January and February are above the threshold
value_lost_jan_feb_w_frequency <- jan_feb_value_visitor_frequency * 0.28
value_lost_jan_feb_w_frequency # $87,624.58 lost in value!
[1] 87624.58

We think this method is robust, as has similar values to another economic analysis via BEACON that values recreation for Santa Barbara County beaches. Our values are fairly similar to theirs, despite the fact that we used simulated data.
